I've posted up many of the interesting murals the team at Saint John's Church on Princes Street create. Many, including their Christmas and Easter ones, still carry social and political and moral commentary (a favourite was a Christmas one few years ago, painting of cash register, shoppers and "glory to God in the High Street"). Often they are as clever and interesting as the best editorial cartoons in the newspapers, and I love that they put them up in the shadow of the Castle facing one of the busiest streets in the capital.

This year's though is fairly simple, just a lovely portrait of Nelson Mandela and that smile. Simple, elegant but a nice reminder there is always hope in the darkest times, that the dawn always comes but we have to work to make that dawn happens and for all to share in that rising light and warmth. With so many people in our 'economic recovery' relying on charity food banks and losing their homes while multi millionaire cabinet ministers tell us we must make cuts and sacrifices (I don't see them doing that) it's important to remember that. And for those of us for whom this time of year brings sad memories of the gaps at the Christmas table, the loved ones gone forever and how we feel that ache more keenly at this time of year, again we need to remember the sun will rise again, the wheel will turn, and we need to keep trying. It's bloody hard sometimes, I know that all too well, but we owe it to ourselves, to those we loved and lost and to our fellow beings on this remarkable world shining in the dark of space to try. Merry Christmas, folks.

We had our annual Christmas trip around Edinburgh today, Mum and me. Normally it's on her birthday but as we'll be away then we went round today instead. Mum loves Christmas. She loves Christmas, primarily, I think, because she hates the dark. All those northern hemisphere, mid-winter festivals are just bonkers about light. My good, solid, post-modern education taught me to distrust dichotomies. Sure, there are deep and dangerous outcomes from a light-good, dark-bad mindset. Sure, we need the darkness as much as we need the light (you're speaking to a woman who grew up with shutters in the country and so now sleeps with a pillow on her face to eradicate all-night-city light). But as I watch the sun crawl up onto the roof of St Aloysius, pech its way across for a couple of hours and then gladly head back down to bed in the earth just after lunch, I love to turn on the multicoloured lights in the kitchen, or to light the fire at home, or to plooter along Princes Street and see the trees all decked in stars. 

I am thankful for sky sun, and human sun. And one day I will have a SAD lamp and my life will change.

Entrance to the very posh Caledonian Hotel in the West End of Edinburgh's New Town, lit up for Christmas. Formerly a huge railway station (this would have been the entrance to go catch a train) those tracks are long gone but the building remains as one of the poshest hotels in the city, right in view of the Castle.
Couldn't resist zooming in on one of the statues above the entrance to the Caledonian, they seemed almost eerie being uplit like that, begging for a mono night shot.

Jollie’s Close in Edinburgh dates back to the earlier 17th century and was named after Patrick Jollie then later, in 1859, after a writer Alexander Jollie.   

Inside there is a 3-storey and attic rubble-built tenement with stairtower dating to 1635 that now is part of The Witchery suites.  Built on the site of the Palace of Mary de Guise, mother of Mary Queen of Scots, these buildings have variously been the townhouse of an aristocratic family and part of the University's Faculty of Divinity before their recent restoration.
